'''Margaret Chalmers McLarty''', known as '''Margaret McLarty''', (1908–1996)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.3109/17453059609056281 |title=Obituary: Margaret C. McLarty DA, B. Litt, FMAA, MAMI 1908–1996 |website=Journal of Audiovisual Media in Medicine |pages=215–216 |doi=10.3109/17453059609056281 |access-date=2018-03-12}}</ref> was a medical illustrator for the [[anaesthetic]] department in [[Oxford University]]. In 1960 she published ''Illustrating Medicine and Surgery''<ref>{{cite book|last=McLarty|first=M. C.|title=Illustrating Medicine and Surgery|year=1960|publisher=E. & S. Livingstone Ltd|location=Edinburgh and London}}</ref> a seminal volume on medical illustration and a core text for medical illustrators. She provided illustrations for the first two editions of ''Anatomy for Anaesthetists''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ellis |first1=Harold |last2= McLarty |first2=Margaret C.|title=Anatomy for Anaesthetists (1st edition)|year=1963|publisher=Blackwell Scientific Publications|location=Oxford}}</ref> written with [[Harold Ellis (professor)|Harold Ellis]] in 1963. 

She was trained by [[Audrey Arnott]] with whom she founded the [[Medical Artists Association of Great Britain]] on 2 April 1949.

